<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 73, 920, 125]]<|/det|>
Two particles \(P\) and \(Q\), of masses \(0.3 \mathrm{kg}\) and \(0.2 \mathrm{kg}\) respectively, are at rest on a smooth horizontal plane. \(P\) is projected at a speed of \(4 \mathrm{m s}^{-1}\) directly towards \(Q\). After \(P\) and \(Q\) collide, \(Q\) begins to move with a speed of \(3 \mathrm{m s}^{-1}\).

<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 136, 465, 156]]<|/det|>

<mark>[2]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[111, 510, 920, 546]]<|/det|>

Over a distance of \(d\mathrm{m}\), the speed of the cyclist increases from \(6\mathrm{m}\mathrm{s}^{- 1}\) to \(12\mathrm{m}\mathrm{s}^{- 1}\).

Two particles \(P\) and \(Q\), of masses \(0.3 \mathrm{kg}\) and \(0.2 \mathrm{kg}\) respectively, are attached to the ends of a light inextensible string. The string passes over a fixed smooth pulley at \(B\) which is attached to two inclined planes. \(P\) lies on a smooth plane \(AB\) which is inclined at \(60^{\circ}\) to the horizontal. \(Q\) lies on a plane \(BC\) which is inclined at \(30^{\circ}\) to the horizontal. The string is taut and the particles can move on lines of greatest slope of the two planes (see diagram).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[116, 447, 146, 465]]<|/det|>
<label>(a)</label>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 446, 816, 465]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[156, 477, 818, 496]]<|/det|>

A particle \(P\) moves in a straight line through a point \(O\). The velocity \(\nu \mathrm{m} \mathrm{s}^{- 1}\) of \(P\), at time \(t \mathrm{s}\) after passing \(O\), is given by

<|ref|>equation<|/ref|><|det|>[[406, 109, 591, 144]]<|/det|>
\[\nu = \frac{9}{4} +\frac{b}{(t + 1)^2} -ct^2,\]

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[118, 150, 920, 170]]<|/det|>
